@Imene DAHANE The problem is that the Spring Security is not understanding it has to be stateless, so it is saving the jwt key like in a kind of session. 
To resolve this issue, we need to make the Spring Security do the API stateless. In order to do that go to your SecurityConfig class and add this: 

.and().sessionManagement()
                .sessionCreationPolicy(SessionCreationPolicy.STATELESS);

after the ".authenticated(); piece of code. 

Doing this your API will turn stateless, that means it will have to be authenticated in every call.

